T1  - Clarifying the Entrepreneurial Orientation Construct and Linking It To Performance
AU  - Lumpkin, G. T.
AU  - Dess, Gregory G.
Y1  - 1996/01/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1996.9602161568
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1996.9602161568
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 135
EP  - 172
VL  - 21
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The primary purpose of this article is to clarify the nature of the entrepreneurial orientation (EO) construct and to propose a contingency framework for investigating the relationship between EO and firm performance. We first explore and refine the dimensions of EO and discuss the usefulness of viewing a firm's EO as a multidimensional construct. Then, drawing on examples from the EO-related contingencies literature, we suggest alternative models (moderating effects, mediating effects, independent effects, interaction effects) for testing the EO-performance relationship.
AB  - The primary purpose of this article is to clarify the nature of the entrepreneurial orientation (EO) construct and to propose a contingency framework for investigating the relationship between EO and firm performance. We first explore and refine the dimensions of EO and discuss the usefulness of viewing a firm's EO as a multidimensional construct. Then, drawing on examples from the EO-related contingencies literature, we suggest alternative models (moderating effects, mediating effects, independent effects, interaction effects) for testing the EO-performance relationship.
